How can we handle large data in SpringBoot application 
1. Pagination and Sorting
Instead of loading all records, fetch them in smaller chunks.Reduces memory usage and improves response time
2. Streaming Large Data
Use Java 8 Streams or JPA streaming to process large datasets without loading all at once.
@Query("SELECT e FROM Employee e")
Stream<Employee> streamAllEmployees();

try (Stream<Employee> stream = employeeRepository.streamAllEmployees()) {
    stream.forEach(emp -> process(emp));
}
3. Batch Processing
Use Spring Batch to process and write large volumes of data in chunks.
 4. Asynchronous Processing
If processing large data takes time, run it in the background.
6. Caching
Use Spring Cache or Redis to reduce repetitive database calls.

@Cacheable("employees")
public List<Employee> getAllEmployees() {
    return employeeRepository.findAll();
7. Use DTOs Instead of Entities
Only fetch required fields using DTO projections.

| Strategy        | Use Case                                |
| --------------- | --------------------------------------- |
| Pagination      | Displaying/searching large tables       |
| Streaming       | Reading millions of records efficiently |
| Spring Batch    | ETL jobs, scheduled data loads          |
| Asynchronous    | Background processing                   |
| DTO Projections | Optimized data fetching                 |
| Redis Caching   | Fast access to frequently used data     |
| Message Queues  | Distribute load                         |
| File Streaming  | Upload/download large files             |


Pagination is the process of dividing a large set of data into smaller chunks (pages).
✅ Example: If you have 10,000 records, you can show 100 records per page — making it 100 pages.

🔹 What is Sorting?
Sorting is the process of arranging the data based on one or more fields.
✅ Example: Sort employees by name in ascending or descending order.

🔹 Spring Data JPA Support
Spring provides Pageable, Page, and Sort interfaces to handle pagination and sorting.

@Entity
public class Employee {
    @Id
    private Long id;
    private String name;
    private int age;
}

public interface EmployeeRepository extends JpaRepository<Employee, Long> {
}
Since JpaRepository already extends PagingAndSortingRepository, it provides:

Page<Employee> findAll(Pageable pageable);
🔹 2. Pagination + Sorting Controller 

@GetMapping("/employees")
public Page<Employee> getEmployees( @RequestParam(defaultValue = "0") int page,  @RequestParam(defaultValue = "5") int size,  @RequestParam(defaultValue = "id") String sortBy) {
    Pageable pageable = PageRequest.of(page, size, Sort.by(sortBy));
    return employeeRepository.findAll(pageable);
}
✅ Explanation:
page=0: First page (0-based index)

size=5: 5 records per page

sortBy=id: Sort records by id column
GET /employees?page=1&size=5&sortBy=name
This fetches the second page with 5 employees sorted by name.


NoClassDefFoundError occurs when:

The class was available at compile time, but Java cannot find it at runtime.

It is an Error, not an Exception.

Hierarchy:

Throwable
 ├── Exception
 └── Error
      └── LinkageError
           └── NoClassDefFoundError
Scenario 1: Class deleted after compilation
Step 1

Create class:

public class Employee {
}
Step 2

Use it:

public class Test {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Employee e = new Employee();
    }
}

Compile successfully:

javac Employee.java Test.java
Step 3

Delete:

Employee.class
Step 4

Run:

java Test

Output:

Exception in thread "main"
java.lang.NoClassDefFoundError: Employee

Why?

Compile Time  -> Employee.class exists ✓
Runtime       -> Employee.class missing ✗
Scenario 2: Missing Dependency JAR

Suppose your code uses:

import com.mysql.cj.jdbc.Driver;

Compilation succeeds because:

mysql-connector-j.jar

was present.

But during runtime, if the JAR is missing:

java.lang.NoClassDefFoundError:
com/mysql/cj/jdbc/Driver
Scenario 3: Spring Boot Example

Suppose you add:

<dependency>
    <groupId>io.jsonwebtoken</groupId>
    <artifactId>jjwt-api</artifactId>
</dependency>

but forget:

jjwt-impl
jjwt-jackson

Application may compile, but when generating/parsing JWTs at runtime:

java.lang.NoClassDefFoundError

because required implementation classes are missing.

Difference between ClassNotFoundException and NoClassDefFoundError
ClassNotFoundException	NoClassDefFoundError
Checked Exception	Error
Happens when JVM tries to load a class dynamically	Happens when class existed during compilation but missing during runtime
Usually with Class.forName()	Usually due to missing .class file or JAR

Example:

Class.forName("com.mysql.cj.jdbc.Driver");

If not found:

ClassNotFoundException
Interview Answer

When do we get NoClassDefFoundError?

We get NoClassDefFoundError when a class was present during compilation but is unavailable at runtime. Common reasons include missing JAR files, deleted .class files, incorrect classpath configuration, or deployment issues. It is an Error and occurs during class loading by the JVM.

Easy Memory Trick
Class available during compile time ✅
Class missing during runtime ❌

=> NoClassDefFoundError


The onboarding process starts in the React application, where the user fills out the OCA form and submits it. 
The frontend sends a POST request to our Customer Onboarding Spring Boot service. The controller validates the request, 
and we perform additional business validations, such as checking for mandatory fields and duplicate customer records. 
The service layer processes the request and persists the data to the database using Spring Data JPA. Depending on the business flow,
we also invoke other internal microservices via REST APIs to retrieve or update related information. If any downstream service is unavailable,
we handle the exception appropriately, log the error, and return a meaningful response. Once the onboarding is approved, the prospect customer is converted into a payer customer


1. How does an ArrayList grow internally?

"ArrayList stores elements in an internal array. When the array becomes full, it creates a new, larger array (typically about 1.5 times the current capacity in modern JDKs), 
copies the existing elements into it, and then adds the new element."

This resizing is why adding an element is usually fast, but occasionally more expensive when a resize happens.

2. Why is insertion at the beginning O(n)?

Suppose:
[A, B, C, D]
If you insert X at index 0, it becomes:

[X, A, B, C, D]
Every existing element has to shift one position to the right, so the work grows with the number of elements: O(n).

Adding at the end is usually O(1) because you simply place the new element in the next available slot. Only when the internal array is full does resizing make that single insertion more expensive.

