"When the application starts, the main() method calls SpringApplication.run(). This creates the Spring Application Context.
@SpringBootApplication combines @Configuration, @EnableAutoConfiguration, and @ComponentScan. 
Component scanning discovers beans like @Controller, @Service, @Repository, and @Component, then creates and registers them in the IoC container.
Auto-configuration configures beans based on the dependencies available on the classpath, such as DispatcherServlet, DataSource, and JPA.
Finally, the embedded Tomcat server starts, and the application begins listening for incoming HTTP requests."


======================================

When the Spring application starts, it scans the classes and creates beans for classes annotated with @Component, @Service, @Repository, and @Controller.
During dependency injection, Spring sees the @Autowired annotation on EmployeeService. It looks into the ApplicationContext for a bean of type EmployeeService.
If exactly one matching bean exists, Spring injects it. If multiple beans of the same type exist, Spring throws NoUniqueBeanDefinitionException unless we use @Qualifier 
or mark one bean with @Primary."
